der low light, and have high$\backslash$ndispersal. In contrast, species that grow slowly under high light$\backslash$ntend to cast relatively dark shade, and to have high survivorship$\backslash$nunder low light and low dispersal. These trade-offs define one of$\backslash$ntwo dominant {"}axes{"} of strategic variation. 3) Community level predictions$\backslash$nof the model. The model predicts succession from early dominance$\backslash$nby species such as Quercus rubra and Prunus serotina, to late dominance$\backslash$nby Fagus grandifolia and Tsuga canadensis, with Betula alleganiensis$\backslash$npresent as a gap phase species in old-growth stands. The model also$\backslash$npredicts that old-growth communities will have intraspecifically$\backslash$nclumped and interspecifically segregated spatial distributions. 4)$\backslash$nAn error analysis that identifies community level predictions that$\backslash$nare robust given the level of sampling uncertainty in the study.$\backslash$nThis analysis translates the statistical uncertainty associated with$\backslash$neach parameter estimate into statistical uncertainty in the model's$\backslash$npredictions. The robust predictions include those mentioned in aspect$\backslash$n(3) above. 5) Sensitivity of the model to changes in initial conditions$\backslash$nand to changes in the three parameters not included in the error$\backslash$nanalysis. For example, the model predicts that initial abundances$\backslash$ncontinue to affect community composition well into succession ({\textgreater}$\backslash$n300 yr for some species). 6) Tests of the system- and community-level$\backslash$npredictions of the model against independent data gleaned from other$\backslash$nstudies. These tests support the predictions found to be robust in$\backslash$nthe error analysis, including those predictions mentioned in aspect$\backslash$n(3) above. 7) Modeling experiments that determine which aspects of$\backslash$nindividual performance and 